Window seat, please. üí∫‚Å£
‚Å£
This view from a window on the SpaceX Dragon Freedom spacecraft looks out at Baja California Sur and the Gulf of California as it was docked to the International Space Station (@iss) orbiting 261 miles (420 kilometers) above the Pacific Ocean.‚Å£
‚Å£
This Dragon spacecraft journeyed to the @iss to deliver the #Crew5 space travelers to the orbiting laboratory.‚Å£
‚Å£
Imagine you had a window seat to anywhere in the universe. Where would you want to go?‚Å£
‚Å£
Image Description: The oval window of the SpaceX Crew Dragon spacecraft frames the curvature of Earth and highlights the Baja California peninsula, surrounded by blue waters.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: NASA/Kjell Lindgren‚Å£
‚Å£
#NASA #Space #SpaceX #WindowSeat #Travel #Traveling #FlyAway #Earth

Time for some Sun salutations üßò‚Å£
‚Å£
Flow through a week of solar activity, from Nov. 1 to Nov. 8, 2022, as captured by our Solar Dynamics Observatory or SDO. From its orbit in space around Earth, SDO has steadily imaged the Sun in 4k resolution for nearly 13 years. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Looking for a longer solar soundtrack to power your practice? Checkout youtube.com/NASA/community for a full 133 days of solar observations to the tune of lo-fi beats. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Video description: Mellow music plays as compiled images taken every 108 seconds condenses 7 days of solar observations, between Nov. 1 and Nov. 8 into 23 seconds. The video shows bright active regions passing across the face of the Sun as it rotates.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: @nasagoddard, Scott Wiessinger (Lead Producer and editor), Tom Bridgman (Lead Visualizer), Lars Leonhard (Music)‚Å£
‚Å£
#NASA #Sun #Solarsystem #SolarPower #SunSalutations #SDO #Space #Star

node.text:
Three Amigos‚Å£
‚Å£
@NASAHubble, @NASAChandraXray, and NASA's Spitzer Space Telescope captured the heart of our Milky Way galaxy using two different spectrums of light, infrared and X-ray. The telescopes peered through the dust and debris that obscure the core of our galaxy ‚Äì which is visible as the bright white region to the right and just below the center of the image.‚Å£
‚Å£
The Hubble telescope ‚Äì which typically captures the cosmos in visible light ‚Äì unveils the stellar winds and radiation that our heated by massive stars that make up the galactic center region in infrared, seen here in yellow and gold. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Spitzer also viewed our galaxy in infrared in a more detailed view and showed the turbulent core of the galaxy, which consists of hundreds of thousands of stars and stellar nurseries ‚Äì areas that create the next generation of stars. Spitzer's view is seen in red and orange.‚Å£
‚Å£
Our Chandra X-ray Observatory shows the galactic core in pink and blue, where pink represents lower energy X-rays, and blue represents higher energy. A supermassive black hole at the center of our galaxy diffuses X-ray light in the bottom right of the image.‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: Swirling colors of red, orange, yellow, gold, pink, and blue dominate this image. At the middle-bottom-right of the photo, the core of our galaxy shines bright. Interstellar dust and radiation combine to create a brilliant tapestry backed by the blackness of space.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/ESA/CXC/STScI‚Å£
‚Å£
#MilkyWay #Stars #Core #Galaxy #NASA #Space #Telescope

node.text:
Lucky Streak‚Å£.
‚Å£
Each January, the Quadrantids Meteor Shower peaks for a few hours, giving spectators some of the best potential annual meteor shower views. Most easily seen in the Northern Hemisphere this year on Jan. 3, the Quadrantids are known for their bright fireball meteors, and as many as 60 to 200 meteors can be seen per hour in ideal conditions. However, in 2023, a nearly full Moon may wash out many shooting stars, if you can see the sky at all through January clouds.‚Å£
‚Å£
So, how about a virtual meteor experience instead? The image above was captured by astronaut Ron Garan in 2011 from the @ISS and shows a Perseid meteor. Meteors, sometimes known as shooting stars, are roughly pebble-sized meteoroid or comet that enters our atmosphere and are typically vaporized.‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: Green and dim yellow airglow appears as thin layers visible above the limb of the Earth, extending from image left to upper image right. Atoms and molecules above 50 kilometers in the atmosphere are excited by sunlight during the day, and then release this energy at night producing primarily green light observable from orbit. The sun is low on the horizon as it appears near part of one of the station's solar panel arrays at image upper right. A lone Perseid meteor appears as a bright streak near the center of the image.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: NASA/Ron Garan‚Å£
‚Å£
#MeteorShower #Atmosphere #SpaceStation #Earth #NASA #Space #Quadrantids #ShootingStars #MakeAWish

All year long, our NASA Headquarters photographers capture historic launches, landings, and milestones. Visit their Flickr album to see their top 100 photos from 2022: flickr.com/nasahqphoto‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Copy and paste the direct album link:‚Å£‚Å£
https://flic.kr/s/aHBqjAmryH‚Å£‚Å£

Image description for photo one: This composite made from ten images shows the progression of the Moon during a total lunar eclipse above the Vehicle Assembly Building, Nov. 8, 2022, at NASA‚Äôs Kennedy Space Center in Florida. Visible trailing the Moon in this composite is Mars. From left to right, the Moon starts off at its usual brightness and gradually becomes a dull red. Credit: NASA/Joel Kowsky‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description for photo two: The SpaceX Crew Dragon Freedom spacecraft descends to Earth with four parachutes that resemble jellyfish. The four chutes are fully deployed and the candy corn-shaped capsule dangles below. The sky looks clear and blue. Credit: NASA/Bill Ingalls‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Image description for photo three: Boeing and NASA teams in protective gear work around Boeing‚Äôs CST-100 Starliner capsule after it landed at White Sands Missile Range‚Äôs Space Harbor, Wednesday, May 25, 2022, in New Mexico. The capsule is gray and it sits atop its beige airbags which deployed moments before touchdown in the desert. Workers access the top of the capsule via ladder. Boeing‚Äôs Orbital Flight Test-2 (OFT-2) was Starliner‚Äôs second uncrewed flight test to the International Space Station as part of NASA's Commercial Crew Program. Credit: NASA/Bill Ingalls‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
Image description for photo four: Nighttime closeup of the fiery exhaust from the launch of a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket carrying the Surface Water and Ocean Topography, or SWOT, satellite aboard, Friday, Dec. 16, 2022, from Space Launch Complex 4E at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California. A bright column of flames dominates the image and creates puffy clouds. Image taken moments after liftoff. Credit: NASA/Keegan Barber‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
#NASA #Photography #Eclipse #Space #Rockets #Launch #SpaceX #Boeing #Liftoff

You don‚Äôt look a day over 4.5 billion-years. ‚òÄÔ∏è‚Å£
‚Å£
#HappyNewYear from the star of the show that makes all this possible, as we begin a new orbit around our Sun, 93 million miles (150 million km) from Earth. Cosmically middle-aged and classified as a yellow dwarf, the Sun's dynamic and ever-changing nature constantly sends energy into the solar system. Scientists can estimate the age of the Sun by looking at the most ancient things in our solar system, which along with the Sun, all formed around the same time.
‚Å£
The Sun is at the center of our solar system, 865,000 miles wide (1.4 million km) with a core that reaches temperatures of 27 million degrees Fahrenheit (15 million degrees Celsius). Our Sun‚Äôs gravity holds our solar system together, from the largest planets to the smallest space debris. ‚Å£
‚Å£
A fleet of spacecraft monitors the Sun 24/7, broadening our knowledge of the star in a branch of science known as heliophysics ‚Äì including the spacecraft that took this image: the Solar Dynamic Observatory (SDO). ‚Å£
‚Å£
The SDO orbits Earth in a geosynchronous pattern ‚Äì it maintains a figure-eight path over the longitude of New Mexico. Because of its orbit, it is constantly in view of radio antennas on Earth; it also enters an eclipse season twice a year when the spacecraft slips behind Earth for up to 72 minutes a day, obscuring the Sun with Earth‚Äôs shadow as seen here.‚Å£
‚Å£
Image description: Black space surrounds the Sun, which glows and swirls in red, orange, and spots of yellow and is shrouded by the shadow of Earth. Eruptions spot the edges of the star, sending material into space.‚Å£
‚Å£
Credit: NASA/GSFC/SDO‚Å£
‚Å£
#Sun #SolarSystem #Earth #SDO #Star #Planets

Ring in the new year! ü™ê
 
We‚Äôre celebrating like it‚Äôs 1999‚Äîthe year that @NASAHubble captured this image of Saturn, the sixth planet from our Sun. 

Hubble took several photos of Saturn between 1996 and 2000, observing how its rings appear differently from our perspective as the gas giant makes its 29-year-long journey around the Sun. For instance, when Saturn‚Äôs rings are viewed from their edge on, they seem to be small and thin. However, when the planet‚Äôs orbit has moved enough that they can be viewed from an angle, the full picturesque breadth of Saturn‚Äôs iconic rings can be seen. 
 
The particles that make up Saturn‚Äôs rings mostly range from tiny, dust-sized icy grains to chunks as big as a house, with a few particles as large as mountains. Saturn's rings are thought to be pieces of comets, asteroids, or shattered moons that broke up before they reached the planet, torn apart by its powerful gravity. One of the most impressive sights in our solar system, Saturn continues to allure astronomers, with recent @NASAWebb observations targeting its largest moon Titan. Saturn has also been visited by four robotic missions‚Äîincluding our Cassini spacecraft, which dove into the planet's atmosphere in 2017.
 
Image Description: Saturn and its rings. The warm brown-and-creme hues of Saturn‚Äôs cloudy atmosphere present a gradient of color against the dark blackness of space. At its south pole, the darkest shades of the ombr√© pattern create a circle of earthy brown. Circling Saturn, grey rings are intersected by the Cassini Division, a gap measuring 2,920 miles (4,700 kilometers), which breaks up the otherwise halo-like rings. 
 
Credit: NASA and The Hubble Heritage Team (STScI/AURA); Acknowledgment: R.G. French (Wellesley College), J. Cuzzi (NASA/Ames), L. Dones (SwRI), and J. Lissauer (NASA/Ames)
 
#NASA #Space #NewYear #NewYearsEve #Saturn #Hubble #Telescope #Planet #SolarSystem

node.text:
What‚Äôs Up? üéº

If you wake up in the morning and step outside, and take a deep breath and look real high‚Äîthere‚Äôs no need to scream from the top of your lungs: here‚Äôs what‚Äôs going on. Throughout January, a newly discovered comet may be seen gliding across the sky towards the northwest in the Northern Hemisphere, with visibility in the Southern Hemisphere beginning in February. 

January brings ample opportunity to gaze upon the bright constellations of winter: looking towards the south or southeast after dark you‚Äôll spy the Orion, Canis Major, Canis Minor, Taurus, and Gemini constellations shining in the night sky. After the sun sets, skygazers will also be treated to the sights of Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn all month long. Plus, expect the full "Wolf" Moon on Jan. 6. 

Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech

#NASA #Space #Stars #Moon #Venus #Mars #Jupiter #Saturn #WolfMoon #Comet #Stargazing #4NonBlondes #HEYYEYAAEYAAAEYAEYAA
